passages.text: Feedback from post- results management meeting
We hosted Stockland management for a post- results briefing in Melbourne earlier this week. Our key takeaways are outlined below.

- Melbourne to improve over the next six months. Stock overhang is reducing and so are incentives. Investors and builders are leading demand, with owner occupiers likely to follow, as typically happens.- SEQ - saw further strength in the market over the final quarter of FY25 and this has carried into the start of FY26.- Sydney - solid performance despite lack of affordability, minimal FHB (less than 10%). Limited supply and price growth running at \(\sim 3\) to \(5\%\) .- Perth - peaked \(\sim 12\) months ago, moderated but has seen renewed price and volume in the last quarter, assisted by rate cuts.- Lendlease portfolio acquisition - is performing better than expected (terms agreed Dec-23) with price growth and sales volume (ex Vic) running ahead of original feasibilities.- MCP guidance (7,500-8,500 lot settlements in FY26) implies \(\sim 1,900\) net deposits a quarter to get to the bottom end of its settlement target.- Apartments - over the long-term, Sydney has been the best performing residential market in Australia, and Stockland wants to have exposure to this market. There are limited MPC opportunities in Sydney with mostly brownfield opportunities requiring apartment development. SGP is trying to secure capital-efficient sites and will look to bring in capital partners prior to commencing construction on its apartment projects.- Land lease - Stockland sees its capital employed at about the right level for land lease. It aims to lift FY25's 530 settlement to 700-800 in FY26 and to \(\sim 1,000\) over the medium term. Stockland would be unlikely to look at LIC as it doesn't like DMF.- Kingscliff - Stockland has acquired a \(\sim 857\) ha site with approval for \(\sim 4,500\) homes near Kingscliff in northern NSW from Leda Holdings. Press suggested a price of \(\sim \$ 620\) . Stockland noted it was a multi-stage payment for the project, with the first payment due on Jul-26. The price paid includes the first \(\sim 350\) lots which are already developed, and Stockland is very optimistic about the project, noting strong demand and limited nearby supply.

SGP has a high- quality residential business and its land bank is well in- the- money. It has grown its Land Lease business via acquisitions and is accelerating the development rollout. It has a diversified investment portfolio and has been growing its industrial portfolio through acquisitions and developments and reducing its retail exposure. We are constructive on the medium- term fundamentals for Australian residential housing, and note a solid pick- up in sales activity in the last quarter of FY25 after two to three years of subdued activity. SGP trades at \(\sim 1.45x\) book value, which is a significant premium to its diversified peers and above its historic range. On relative valuation, we are Underweight.

Our Jun- 26 price target of \(60.00 (+50\epsilon)\) is due to our earnings upgrades and our review of our discount rate. Our Price Target is based on the mid- point of our NAV and the roll- forward of our NPV. For the NAV, we assume trust book values lift \(3\%\) on Jun- 25 levels. Our NAV average cap rate is \(6.2\%\) and we use a DCF on the Communities business that equates to \(\sim 2.5x\) book value. Our NPV is calculated using five years of AFFO, a beta of 0.68 and a discount rate of \(8.6\%\) . We use a \(4.0\%\) risk- free rate, \(2.5\%\) long- term growth rate, and a \(6.0\%\) equity risk premium.

Commercial development pipeline activity has increased - interest rate moves and cap rate stabilisation have made it more favourable to develop. Stockland has outlined a \(\) 9.7\(bn logistics pipeline,\) \ \(0.7\) bn retail, \(\) 0.5\(bn alternates (medical, childcare) and\) \ \(5.3\) bn mixed- use / workplace pipeline.

It expects a stronger commercial development profit contribution in FY26, noting it has \(\sim\) 300m of industrial build- to- suit projects at Melbourne Business Park and Kemps Creek expected to be completed this year at a target margin of \(\sim 15\%\) . It noted it doesn't have a big pipeline behind these two projects so is unlikely to be a material ongoing profit contributor. Apartment sell- downs to a JV partner and data centre sell downs are potential future contributors to replace the expected industrial development profits in FY26.

SGP has reactivated its retail pipeline, with three active projects under development and another five potential projects. Retail projects at its MPC estates have historically been loss- leading and used to drive stronger residential sales. But Stockland notes supermarkets are paying higher rents, lifting the development yields on cost to \(\sim 6 - 7\%\) .

Kogarah - a 50:50 JV with John Boyd Properties, was originally targeted as a residential development prior to COVID. SGP has made a minimal payment upfront. The site will be developed into \(\sim 340,000\mathrm{sqm}\) of industrial over five levels and will be undertaken in three stages. SGP will require pre- commitments prior to starting construction.

Yennora - \(\mathbb{S}840\mathrm{m}\) book value, 300,000sqm of GLA and \(\) 41.4\(m of FFO (21\% of industrial FFO). Stockland is undertaking a\) 40,000sqm development with \(>50\%\) pre- commitment and is targeting a high \(6\%\) yield on cost. Stockland is expected to roll through the 70 ha site with multiple knock down and rebuild projects, capturing the material under- renting in place \(\sim\) 140/sqm in place rents vs market well into the \(\) 200\('s/sqm\).

Stockland sees capital partnering as its primary source of capital. It has raised \(\sim\) 3bn from partnerships in the last three years. The DRP has been reactivated and Stockland has lowered its payout ratio at this result to assist with funding its expanded development pipeline.

- 100MW across two sites at Macquarie Park. Stockland believes it has further opportunities in Sydney and Melbourne and will provide more details as it secures power.- Stockland is not an operator of data centres and does not want to become one, but customers are wanting a one-stop solution, hence its newly established partnership with Edge Connex. The agreement provides exclusivity to each other for DC opportunities within Australia for a period of time. Stockland will contribute land sites to the JV at data centre approved land values and will likely bring in additional capital partners at the appropriate time. It sees the possibility of land sale profits being realised when selling into the JV, but isn't expecting much from M_Park given elevated land values for the site, which has apartment and data centre approval on it.
Stockland (Underweight; Price Target: A\(6.00)
